3. Make.com Scenario Setup
3.1 Webhook Trigger
The scenario is initiated by a custom webhook created in Make.com under the Webhooks module. The webhook generates a unique URL that acts as the entry point for the entire automation.
The webhook URL is registered on cron-job.org to fire automatically every 30 minutes by sending a POST request. The same webhook URL is also embedded in the Lovable dashboard's Run Monitor button for manual on-demand triggering.
To create the webhook in Make.com:
•   	Add a Webhooks → Custom webhook module as the first module
•   	Click Add to generate the unique webhook URL
•   	Copy the URL and paste it into cron-job.org as a new cronjob set to POST every 30 minutes
3.2 Google Sheets — Clear Values
Immediately after the webhook and before the Router, a Google Sheets → Clear Values module wipes the Latest tab clean. This ensures the Lovable UI dashboard always reflects only the most recent scenario run rather than accumulating historical rows.
Configuration:
•   	Spreadsheet: Crypto Watcher (your Google Sheet)
•   	Sheet: Latest
•   	Range: A2:I1000 — clears all data rows while preserving the header row in Row 1
3.3 Router
A Router module immediately after the Clear Values module splits the scenario into two independent branches. Each branch runs completely separately with its own data sources, iterators and notification channels.
•   	Branch 1 (labelled Price Change) — monitors three tracked coins for significant price movements. Note: I used only 3 coins (bitcoin, ethereum and Solana) to avoid pulling a lot of data and I am also in free plan.
•   	Branch 2 (labelled Fallback/Trending) — independently fetches and notifies about globally trending coins
 
 
4. Branch 1 — Price Monitoring
4.1 HTTP Module — Fetch Market Data
The first HTTP module on Branch 1 calls the CoinGecko /coins/markets endpoint to retrieve live market data for the three tracked coins in a single API call.
 
