5. Branch 2 — Trending Coins
5.1 HTTP Module — Fetch Trending Coins
The second branch operates completely independently from Branch 1. It fetches the current global trending coins from CoinGecko's dedicated trending endpoint. No parameters are required — the endpoint always returns the top 7 coins trending on CoinGecko based on search volume in the last 24 hours.
GET https://api.coingecko.com/api/v3/search/trending
This branch is not limited to the three coins tracked in Branch 1. It monitors the entire CoinGecko platform for any coin gaining traction globally, satisfying the requirement to notify about newly trending or listed coins.



5.2 Iterator
An Iterator loops through the coins[] array returned by the trending endpoint. Unlike Branch 1 which uses Data[], this Iterator points to the coins[] key specifically since the trending endpoint nests its array inside a coins property.
This produces up to 7 individual bundles — one per trending coin — which then each proceed independently to the Slack notification and Google Sheets logging.
5.3 Slack — Trending Coin Notification
A Slack module sends a formatted message to a configured public Slack channel for each trending coin. The connection uses OAuth authentication through Make.com's Slack integration.
Message format used:
 
🔥 Trending Coin
Coin Name: {{8.item.name}}
Symbol: {{8.item.symbol}}
Price: ${{8.item.data.price}}
Volume: {{8.item.data.total_volume}}
Market Cap: {{8.item.data.market_cap}}
Market Cap Rank: {{8.item.market_cap_rank}}
Image: {{8.item.small}}


5.4 Google Sheets — Log Trending Coins
Two Google Sheets modules on Branch 2 log each trending coin to both tabs identically to Branch 1. The Alert Type column is set to the static text 'Trending Alert' so the Lovable dashboard can filter and display trending coins separately from price alert coins.
6. Google Sheets Structure
A single Google Sheet named Crypto Watcher contains two tabs that serve different purposes for the system.
6.1 Latest Tab
The Latest tab is cleared at the start of every scenario run by the Clear Values module and then rewritten with fresh data from both branches. The Lovable dashboard reads exclusively from this tab via a published CSV URL. It always contains only the data from the most recent run — never historical rows.
6.2 History Tab
The History tab is never cleared — it is only ever appended to. Every scenario run adds new rows for all coins processed on both branches. This provides a complete audit log of all price data and alerts over time, useful for trend analysis and documentation.
